column8: Perisher is absolutely huge. The pluses are it caters to all wants and needs and it is difficult to get bored as long as you're hitting the slopes, even after multiple visits - you'll be tired from exhaustion before you get tired of the mountain(s). The minuses are that it is expensive and it relies on a lot of t-bars to get around. But it should be part of the conversation when you are talking about the best snow resorts in the southern hemisphere.

column8: Spent the last 6 days at Perisher on good snow under blue skies. I've never seen such good conditions for 6 consecutive days. The resort has plenty of ski runs for all levels from beginners up. There are several places to eat or grab a coffee all over the resort. They're all a bit pricey but I've come to expect that. For example, a large flat white coffee will set you back $6.90. All the staff on and off the snow that I have had anything to do with have been really nice. It's a great place to learn to ski for kids and adults alike. You can hire skis and boots etc there and there are plenty of shops at the main station to buy any ski apparel or accessories that you need. There is ski-in-ski-out accommodation available as well. I'll be going back in two weeks so if I think of anything else to add I will.

column8:
Beautiful place, lots of good ski runs. In school holidays it can get crowded - with big queues for ski lifts, particularly if a bunch of lifts close due to strong winds. Could also use more areas for people to sit and have lunch. What’s there gets jammed at lunchtime. And the food outlets mostly serve junk. Needs some better restaurants and cafes. I’d give 5 stars for the staff I encountered. Including two terrific ski instructors - Richard and Rich. Learnt heaps and enjoyed their classes. The Perisher website is a bit clunky, but works.

column8:
Ive skiied in Canada and NZ. But learning boarding is tough. The crew at Perisher were super helpful, not just my instructor but the lifties and even the bar staff were giving me tips that eventually got me up and down the mountain many times.
Id also recommend looking at the bundle deals if you need to hire and are thinking about lessons,  works out very reasonable prices.
Loved my time there, ill be back. I still hate T-bars though

column8:
Resort coverage is large enough to get away from the crouds. Typically with a captive audience, prices are elevated but with a wide enough range of choices.
The resort itself combines four smaller resorts and features a large amount of lifts from the V8-Seater monster down to the carpark double, Tee bars (and Jay bars at Smiggins).
With the addition of snowguns and grooming the resort typically sees a good coverage, but when the wind comes in the outer limits of the resort (Perisher Mountain, Guthics and Blue Cow) shut down for safety.
Combine this with purpose built Jindabyne accomodation out at The Station and the SkiTube from Bullocks Flat, which is the best way to visit this resort daily.

column8:
Perisher is old and tired. It poorly lacks modern amenities and decent spaces for people to hang out comfortably in between runs. Everyone handles the outdated and cramped conditions for the sake of the beautiful snow.
The ski tube is an anitquated form of public transport, not worth the  $54 Persher charge for the round trip.
The train is like something you'd board in India; old and overcrowded.
For the amount of profit Perisher makes, it could reinvest in some badly needed and well overdue infrastructure.

column8:
Older children and children under 125 cm cannot get on the lift unless they ask the person in charge for help, as the chair is higher than in Japan (^_^;)
For 8-seaters, the gate closes relatively quickly, so as soon as the gate opens, go forward and get on the conveyor belt to be carried near the lift waiting line. Proceed further to the red line and take the lift there. Turn away children who need help. If you have 8 people, you can get help if you stand on the far left and say one thing.
At the end of July 2018, there was snow all over the course, but there was less snow. There was rain and hail. According to the locals, the real season starts from August onwards.
Tickets are expensive and have your name engraved on a magnetic IC. The sensor's magnetism is strong, so I was warned not to bring my credit card close to it.
The slopes are quite gentle and are full of beginners, many of whom are Indian and Islanders who don't seem to be used to snow, so it's dangerous if you don't watch your surroundings while skiing.
The impression of the ski slope is similar to Sugadaira Kogen. There are no particularly high mountains in sight, and you can ski on all four mountains.
column11:
年長児や125cm以下の子どもは、係の人にhelp pleaseと頼んで乗せてもらわないとリフトの椅子が日本より高くて乗れない～(^_^;)
8人乗りはゲートが割と直ぐに閉まってしまうので、ゲートが開いたら直ぐに前に進み、ベルトコンベアに乗ってリフト待ちライン近くに運んでもらう。更に赤い線まで自分で進み、そこでリフトに乗る。助けが必要な子どもは端にする。8人乗りは左端にして1事言えば助けて貰える。
2018年7月末はコース全体にはあるけど、雪少なめ。雨も雹も降った。地元の人曰く、本格シーズンは８月以降だと言われた。
チケットは高く、磁気ICで名前入り。センサーの磁気が強いので、クレジットカードを近づけないように注意を受けた。
ゲレンデはなだらかな所は結構初心者がいっぱいで、インド系、アイランド系で普段雪に馴染みなさそうな人達が多く、周囲を見ながら滑らないと危険。
ゲレンデの印象は菅平高原の様。特に高い山は見当たらず、4山共通で滑れるようになっている。

column8:
Virtually all food up the mountain contains gluten and/or dairy, which my partner can't eat, and this is annoying. Also why are the bread rolls inevitably the cheapest nastiest bread rolls ever, good bread rolls take up the same amount of space on a skidoo, stop price gouging on stupid things, I don't care if it's up the mountain if you want to charge $20 for a roll it had better be a good roll, until then I'll keep bringing my own food.

The skiing is good though. 4/5 stars, the fifth is on wind hold until they get the bread roll debacle sorted.

column8:
I love the place but I am a bit concerned about some if the changes since ownership changed.

I have experienced more chair lift issues this year than I can remember from previous years.

I have given up hope ever getting value from one of the resort's cafe's, after being stung almost $35 for 2 pies, a large chips and a Pepsi.

Fortunately there is a Woolies in Jindabyne so you can take a much cheaper lunch if you are staying in town.

I wonder if anyone has done the sums on how much more food they would sell if they were not gouging a captive market.

column8: My daughter, cousin and I spent the day at Perisher for some skiing. We had a great time overall, however some service areas could certainly do with some work. The hire centre at the bottom of the snow tube didn't have helpful staff at, compared with the staff at Thredbo who were very careful to properly fit skis and boots, and gave lots of tips for comfort. The runs at Perisher are lovely and far more expansive than Thredbo, but not always clearly marked which, particularly in heavy snow, can make navigation difficult. We frequently ended up around the backs of cabins and struggling to find the runs again. The lessons looked well run, and I like that the ski schools have a line for the lifts so xhildren can be added to lift groups, but unlike elsewhere the instructors didn't bother asking people if they minded helping the kids, and also didn't care that by forcibly pushing in they were separating my child from both of the adults she was with. Not acceptable. I will say though that the food court type area was great, with lots of options and friendly service. The runs were lovely and we will probably return, but hope to find better interpersonal skills from the staff next time.

column8: A great ski resort with lots of nice runs for all levels and good lift system to get the early morning crowds moving. Really helpful staff & good kids program. Good selection of places to eat & drink, plus shops selling ski gear and general necessities. Only rated down one star as its super expensive & for some reason you can't hire tobogans on the mountain (?) Which is frustrating when you pick the kids up from ski school & they have their heart set on tobboganing for the afternoon - you have to hire them at Bullocks Flat or Jindabyne. Although some on-snow hotels have them available as well.

column8:
Perisher is by far the best ski resort in Australia. It is the largest ski resort (was once three ski resorts, but then they all combined to create Perisher). There is ample amounts of lifts, T-bars everywhere to keep you going all day. A wide variety of greens, blue and black runs to suit everyone. Allow time to get up the skitube from the bottom, as it takes approximately 30 minutes. Lots of restaurants scattered around the resort as well! Happily return here, as it's my favourite place to ski.

column8:
Overpriced, some poor quality instructors, huge queues.

Overpriced: $111 for a child half day ticket!, $6 for a water, softdrink or hot chocolate. hotdog with chips ~$20.

Some good/great instructors, some terrible instructors. Some snowboard instructors especially handling the kids shouldn't have the title instructor. Kids spent 3 days in snowboard school and learned practically nothing. Watching from sidelines, snowboard instructors were too busy flirting with each other than teaching the kids.

Queues: V8, Quad, Summit Quad, pretty valley chair all packed to the max. Flowed ok with there was a coordinator packing the lines, but when there wasn't it ran slowly and sometimes waiting 30minutes to get on chair (in morning).

Overpriced, some poor quality instructors, huge queues.

Overpriced: $111 for a child half day ticket!, $6 for a water, softdrink or hot chocolate. hotdog with chips ~$20.

Some good/great instructors, some terrible instructors. Some snowboard instructors especially handling the kids shouldn't have the title instructor. Kids spent 3 days in snowboard school and learned practically nothing. Watching from sidelines, snowboard instructors were too busy flirting with each other than teaching the kids.

column8: Perisher was great; lots of good snow, good machinery to get you up the mountain, and a decent priced holiday. HOWEVER, some of the staff were really rude. For example, when I was coming to the end of the chairlifts, I wasn't a very good snowboarder, so, instead of getting off the chairlifts from the ice that was in-front of me, I decided to get off at the side where there was good grip. Then, the person working at the top started shouting at me asking why I got off there. I said I didn't know where to get off and that I wasn't a good snowboarder, but he continued to shout at me.

column8: Spent the weekend at Perisher. On Saturday they closed all the chairlifts in the morning in anticipation for windy conditions. However the morning was fine. They then opened the lifts in the afternoon when bthe wind picked up. Sunday was great with great weather. Jumpcam near mid station is amazing! Pictures are uploaded to dashboard instantly. Perisher has many chairlifts and alot of variety but could do with longer continuous runs and less flat sections that require traversing.

column8:
Still great snow cover with a solid base late in the season. Its been a while but good to be back. Prices are never going to be cheap (especially with kids) but its good to be sliding down the hill again, good for the soul.
If hiring try jindyabyne in the 1st instance..good gear and advice at competitive pricing (whilst you'll pay top dollar on the mount). We appreciated the help from Craig at Jindabyne sports and Jason from the Base (jindabyne). Jason was on the pulse for price and the complexity of our hire needs..be warned you will pay more... alot more to hire on the mount for the convenience.

column8: Taken during a heavy dumping of snow. One could hardly see the terrain. Roads were frozen over and the wind was gusty. Luckily the resort was well heated and food was available.

column8: I come here every season for atleast 2 weeks at a time. Snow is always great and staff on the resort are always friendly. I took snow boarding classes with a guy by the name of Coby Shultz and dare i say he was the friendliest guy, he also knows so much about snowboarding. Always an awesome time at perisher.

column8: A good experience, visited mid September, conditions were rough at times and snow was fairly icy on the main tracks but still good fun, the powdery off tracks a very fun.

column8:
It was my first time in Perishers and by far one of the best experiences of skiing from around the world. I am told it has 47 lifts, chairs and T bars. I was very lucky to have fresh dump of snow on the last day, it was lots of fun.
Just can't describe it.
Fun for all ages and families big or small, skiers or snowboarders.
Be back next season ...

column8:
Perisher is a great resort with plenty of options on offer.

As the season progresses with more snow the more parks and features become available. I'd like to see a mini pipe again and a quarter pipe setup next season pls. The mini pipe is a great way to learn and get used to dropping in etc. The mid station location was perfect where it was a few years back. Quarter pipe could go in either park near front valley.

Parking is what it is, get there early and you won't have issues in busy times.

What is the area like to play in? Fantastic! So many options and if you wish you will never ski or board the same run in the one day. I usually start over at Eyre and work my way round to Guthega by end of the day and some final runs in Happy Valley, Copperhead Rd and home to front valley. The Superpipe is great when in along with each park area which has many features that work for all levels of skill. Perisher is a place where an advanced rider can find some decent challenging bespoke runs to some great beginner and progressive runs to help you transition into better on snow technique.

The beauty of Perisher is with many different facing aspects of ski areas you can normally find good snow somewhere on resort if you know where to look. Locals are friendly and happy to help in finding those areas of you are nice.

I've found Perisher to be one of the friendliest and good vibe snow fields anywhere I've been. Ski and board people get along mostly haha. It is what it is. But most people are nice and catch the vibe which can lead to great lift conversations and finding the good areas to hit first up.

The learner area is well setup with levels of progression even for learners. Only a good thing!

Mid Station is a great place as is blue cow for a beer and food. Normal resort prices like anywhere though. It costs money to get it all up there so cost is understandable I think.

Future wise what would I like to see?

Year pass separated into just Perisher and then the international one as another add on.

I'd like to see a cross country run like Copperhead Rd but from the top of mount P that runs around the back to Guthega. Used for Ski and board people of an advanced level.

On the transition trails between areas some off trail features would be cool too, like some small ramps etc as a pull over on the way trick for fun.

What would be the best addition? Joining forces with Charlotte's Pass and setting up a chair or gondola or extend the snow train out to Charlotte's so it opens even more up.

Facilities around Perisher, Blue Cow and Guthega are all dated but work well. 99% of the lift staff are great.

Getting to the snow from interstate is a challenge and it would be great to see Perisher advertise deals with Virgin or whoever for fly, drive, stay and ski packages through both Syd and Canberra. From the GC it would be great with a season pass to have a set rate to fly, drive or bus and accommodation at the snow. It would be a game changer.

Then I'd actually consider more weekend trips for a day of snow with travel either side.

I think all resorts, council and state gov need to extend the snow train to Jindy first and Cooma as a second option. It would bring more money and people into the region with them staying at Cooma and other towns on the way. Get Elon's Boring Company into it! A direct train connection out to Jindy from Canberra and Syd would also do nothing but bring more money into the region winter and summer.

column8: I have been to both Perisher and Thredbo and mid July to August is always the best time.  I have always had accommodation on the mountain however Thredbo was the best place to stay plus the choice of restaurants and other activities (large indoor pool for both winter and summer). Perisher at night has only have one pizza shop ( bad service no competition) or boring and expensive hotel food or simple lunch food /snacks cafe food.  The only challenge is Thredbo is lower in altitude and can become soft at the lower levels on sunny days. What I discovered by accident is Jindabyne is beautiful has a larger choice of restaurants compared to Thredbo ( plus has pool and cinema etc). It takes 10 min to drive to the ski tube from Jindabyne which takes you straight to Perisher ski resort, best of both worlds higher mountain and great village atmosphere at the end of the day.

column8:
Unfortunately Perisher seems to be way too focused on profits. They do not re-invest into making the resort better. Certain chairlifts are very old, slow and do not carry many people. These need replacing with newer, faster ones to get people where they need to go. Additionally, there are way too many T-bars which makes much of the resort inaccessible for beginners and snowboarders.

Retail and food outlets are very pricey. The best deal on the mountain was the $2 hot chocolate up at mid- station each morning til 10am. First tracks and night skiing are great and its fantastic that these are free with your Epic Australia pass.

Skitube is a convenient way to get up to Perisher each day, however, this is also quite expensive even if you add it onto your season pass. We were also disappointed that the skitube stopped running during October even though the ski lifts were still open. This made it very difficult to access the resort.

Overall, Perisher needs to invest in improving facilities, replacing old/ slow chairlifts and improve access to areas which are currently T-bar only.

When we visited Snowy Mountains we stayed at Cooma because it's a lot cheaper than Jindabyne. But it's up to your personal preferences of which area you'd like to stay.
Also, the Perisher Ski Resort parking can be packed to prepared to walk a little and do some sight seeing.

column8: Perisher (known as Perisher Blue until 2009) is the largest ski resort in the Southern Hemisphere.[1] Located in the Australian Snowy Mountains, the resort is an amalgamation of four villages (Perisher Valley, Smiggin Holes, Guthega, and Blue Cow) and their associated ski fields, covering approximately 12 square kilometres (5 sq mi), with the base elevation at 1,720 metres (5,640 ft) AHD, and the summit elevation of 2,054 metres (6,739 ft) at the top of Mount Perisher. 4.4 square kilometres (1.7 sq mi) of this area is covered by 240 snow guns, which are used to artificially supplement the natural snowfall.

Feel so lucky every time we get to stay here. The management are lovely, the proximity to the slopes to die for and the food on another level. The entertainment this year was also amazing, the young talented pianist, guitarist and singer - was also carrying our suitcases the next day. This time around we got an upgrade to a suite - had to pinch ourselves. Great place to stay if you have the $ and the inclination to ski in Australia!

column8:
Biggest ski resort in the southern hemisphere, 47 lifts in total. Lots of tracks to ride for beginners and advanced alike. Beautiful place in it's own right.
Would not recommend to rent the gear in the resort if you are under a tight budget. There are several places in Jindabyne (small town 20min away from the resort). Also, bringing your own food for lunch is always an option. Menus offered are not very healthy and quite expensive.
Mind that if you drive to Perisher Valley having chains in your trunk is mandatory in case of snowy days. You can rent chains in petrol stations in Jindabyne

column8:
Largest ski resort in Australia with a mix of easy, moderate and difficult runs. Most runs are easy and the more difficult terrain opens later in the season July/August.

Food is expensive so I I recommend bringing your own. Day pass is expensive so plan ahead and get a season pass at the end of the year September/October for the best deals.

Pro tip - Bluecow is the best place for beginners.

column11:
Largest ski resort in Australia with a mix of easy, moderate and difficult runs. Most runs are easy and the more difficult terrain opens later in the season July/August.

Food is expensive so I I recommend bringing your own. Day pass is expensive so plan ahead and get a season pass at the end of the year September/October for the best deals.

Pro tip - Bluecow is the best place for beginners.

column8:
Took the kids up for the weekend, went to Thredbo on the saturday - this was a mistake as it was mostly mud and parking was poor.
Went to Perisher and it was awesome, large carpark  with easy access to the snow, was a easy safe place for the kids to make a snowman, snow angels a toboggan trips.
The season hadn't really kicked off as it is a week early however everything was in full swings, the skilifts were running and everything was open which was pretty cool.

column8:
Perisher is the largest and most popular ski resort in the Southern Hemisphere and Australia. It encompasses four mountain peaks: Perisher, Smiggin, Blue Cow, and Guthega. There are trails suitable for beginners, intermediate, and advanced skiers. We recommend Guthega for its beautiful scenery and Alpine Eyre for its T-bar-style burger joint. There are night skiing and fireworks every Tuesday and Saturday. The resort uses contactless cards for convenience, and you can also check your ski lift history online or download an app. The downside is that the trails are relatively short and the ski passes are expensive, so avoid visiting during long Australian holidays.

column11: Perisher 是南半球也是澳洲最大且熱門的雪場，含括Perisher、Smiggin、Blue Cow、Guthega四個山頭，初中高階都有適合雪道可玩，推薦Guthega區域風景美、Alpine Eyre需會拉T-BAR才能吃的漢堡店，每週二、六的夜滑還有煙火，雪場用記名感應式卡片方便，也可上網或下載App看自己滑雪纜車紀錄，缺點雪道都偏短，雪票價格也偏貴，避開澳洲連假來吧。

I didn’t stay in the resort however my family and I went to The Perisher ski resort to see snow for the first time, we used the snow slopes for tobogganing which was an amazing time and we used the chair lifts to just take a look around.
There is a ranger gate house on the Kosciuszko road where you can buy your national park vehicle pass the day pass cost us $29. There is a cost to use the chairlifts, a shop to hire any snow sporting accessories or extra snow clothes. If you are in a 4 wheel drive, chains are not needed but it is by law 2wheel drives have to carry snow chains but there is plenty of places in Jindabyne you can hire them from.
Would definitely recommend this place.

column8:
Please read ****
It’s sad that I have to write this review.
I’ve been long long term skier at Perisher me and my family and friends but none of us are going back after last weekend .
Simply after waiting in Wentworth TBat like for 25min
I was pushed away and rejected the ride just because I was a single rider , I understand that it’s  busy and it’s good for everyone to ride double but I tried and I couldn’t find a single to ride but it’s not written anywhere that u can’t ride and u deserve to be pushed away when ur a single rider .
The girls name was Sarah and I told her I will complain and she laughed at me and told me good luck .
I went straight to the office and I was promised a phone call from the manager now it’s been over a week and I haven’t received a call .
It’s u sad for them to loose over 7 riders who ride every second week at Perisher over a very poor costumer service .
Very disappointed.
Don’t go to Perisher

column8: EXTREMELY DISAPPOINTED IN MANAGEMENT AT PERISHER!!!!! I Have bought a seasons pass for 3 years in a row now. My wife was pregnant and we found out at 24 weeks that she had preeclampsia which then developed to HELLP syndrome. This in short started to shut down her body as her liver was failing. The doctors had to deliver our baby boy at 26weeks in order to save her and his life and he is currently in the Neonatal intensive care unit and will be for sometime. I contacted PERISHER and told them situation and said I can get a letter from the hospital regarding this. I Asked them if I could extend my seasons pass to next year as i will be by his side in hospital everyday and will not be able to go down at all. THEY SAID NO. I ASKED FOR A CREDIT NOT A REFUND! VERY DISAPPOINTED!! 😡😡😡

column8:
Perisher ski resort is a massive but good ski resort. They offer a convenient ski tube from bullocks flat to Perisher to Blue Cow.
Fantastic facilities all over the resort including bathrooms, restaurants, bars, ski and snowboard hire and accommodation. There is something here for everyone.  It is also pretty easy to access. Friendly staff and every one is here to have a good time. Totally recommend for your next winter holiday.

column8:
Great place to ski for all levels of skier/boarder. Tonnes of groomers to shred and when there's snow the off-piste is on-point! You're not gonna have the massive vertical mountain experience of some NA or European resorts but there's just so much ground to cover here you'll never be bored. Take a short 5-10min side country hike and you'll be hitting freshies for the whole day.

The Terrain Parks are some of the best in the world with lots of options for beginners all the way up to those massive triple XL's they keep on front valley, a small and large half-pipe just for the icing on the cake.

column8: My favourite Australian ski resort, because it is accessible to a wide range of people with many choices for access. There are slopes that face in many directions so there is a slope for every occasion, and the friendly operators manage access to suit the prevailing snow conditions. There are Lodges and accomodation on site and a range of budget facilities across the field from Perisher, Smiggins, Guthega and Bluecow that will suit anyone and when all connecting lifts are running a wide ranging adventure is possible with a week of exploring and fun on offer. Great fun and adventure.

column8:
The whole resort has not changed in 20 years and shows it. 5 hours of travel for a second rate resort. Inadequate parking, substandard facilities, no lift line organization, very expensive prices for everything - accommodation, lift tickets, food, you name it it's 3 times normal price.
So high I wont be coming back as its now better value flying overseas to places like Canada, where they know how to run ski resorts.
The stranglehold the National parks has on everything is killing it. Good luck.

column8: The lift tickets are VERY pricey (comparable to Vail or Aspen, Colorado) so much so one would think the resort would have modern equipment and chalets.. The chairlifts are from many decades ago (plastic teal slats with no padding or footbars) and are so uncomfortable and slow it was unbelievable. There are two high speed chairs lifts and more T bar lifts than I have ever seen. The chalets remind me of the first chalets I visited from the 80s in the hills of small towns. The entire experience was a blast from the past.  I suppose when you are one of the only resorts in the country to ski there isn't a priority to update/improve the infrastructure.

column8:
Really well layed out resort.  Catch the skitube up to the hill and then go exploring.  The snow is crisp and well groomed and the lifts run well.  Obviously busier on the weekends.  When buying the tickets, add the skitube straight away and save the hassle.  I recommend using the gear hire at the skitube base station, it sounds better than some of the grear being hired off hill from user / friend reports and comparisons.  Bring cash, card isn't that accepted on the hill.

column8:
The lifties  have gotten lazy, felt like they were actively trying to break your legs when getting on at times.
Staff in general weren't as friendly as other resorts in Oz/NZ.
Ski school for kids was haphazard with no continuity between days - i.e. different instructor each day.
Not to mention being stuck on ski tube for close to an hour one afternoon.
Apart from that, great.

column8:
Had a brilliant trip to Perisher with a group of 6 and one child. It was not a busy day so there was lots of parking. Great for families with large toboggan area. A great variety of trails but had no idea where to go based on my skill level as there is no direction other than a huge and confusing map. It would be helpful to have some guides around for people new to the resort. Lots of lifts to choose from and people were really friendly here. As someone new to snowboarding I was pleased to get random advice from various people. Food was especially pricey so take your own or prepare to pay.

Parking and accommodation aren't very well thought out.

column8:
As a resort, its the biggest and most varied runs in Australia.
Food is very expensive, bland and mass produced without care, take homemade sandwiches and buy a tea.
Best accessed from BULLOCKS FLATS as the drive up or down should be avoided during bad weather.
Keep in mind it might be sunny in Jindabyne but no visibility at Perisher.....it has its own micro climate.

column8:
I wish if there was an option for zero star. The entire booking process and customer service is just appalling! The booking site constantly went down. No option to book kids lessons on the first day when I already purchased the lift passes. Then the lessons got booked out suddenly for the days of our lift passes. No option for 1 or 2 days lift passes. No response received  after online enquires sent about the lessons. Telephone is the worst, never able to speak to anyone as it keeps saying technical difficulties with phone line. So my 6 yo daughter is left with 3 days lift pass without lessons. Basically the entire place and management is a dictator. No customer service offered for help at all!

There's no link to purchase the kids lessons. I purchased the 3 day tickets from 27th/06- 29th. Could you contact me for the kids lesson please?

10 days later i finally have a absolutely unconstructive reponse which gives no help at all! Unbelieveable

"Hi

Thank you for contacting Perisher Guest Services.

You can find more information and book children's lessons here.

If you have any further questions please feel free to contact us.

Kind Regards,

Lauren

column8:
Being a season pass holder, and having booked accommodation and purchased a three day ski tube ticket with the promise that season pass holders would not be placed at disadvantage due to other customer ticket purchases; today’s attempts to reserve days for my season pass (which cost $889 AUD) has been absolutely deplorable. I have spend two hours and 26 minutes online attempting to login with the items in my cart being discarded by Perishers sloppy servers many, many times, as well as having the online store close on me and other customers at least four times locking us out completely. There was no explanation of the reservation process prior to today, and there is no ability to contact Perisher by phone, email or social media. This experience so far has been absolutely woeful and of hundreds of fans on social media I have been able to find only three who have secured their reservation.
Absolutely disgraceful Perisher; you knew today was going to be busy yet to made less than the required attempts to ensure your website and customer service was even close to being acceptable.

Unfortunately i had a trip planned and paid for in the July school holidays. Epic season passes for the family and a weeks non refundable accomodation costing many thousands of dollars. A few days before we were due to go Perisher changed their policy and decided we would have to go in an online lucky dip to get a reservation to use our season passes to ski.  We weren't lucky and only got a reservation to ski 2 out of 7 days of our holiday. Other friends going the same time with us who didn't have epic passes were able to buy ski passes for all the days. I have tried to contact Perisher to try and get help with the situation but they don't even answer the phone or emails. Its all been a horrible experience.

I enjoyed skiing every year in this resort. I only gave 3 stars bc it is incomparable to my experience in Hakuba, Japan. I hope they will put toilets at the loading areas so you dont have to go back to the restaurants to use the toilet. The food is a bit pricey esp at Mid-perisher cafe and they don't offer discount for Epic pass holders too. Recently, they have added healthier meal options for vegetarians and vegans at the main restaurants of the resort which is good. A bit busy in mid July to end of August. Some staff are helpful and friendly but most are not maybe bc they are from other countries (backpackers) working at the resort for the season...

column8:
Always good to be part of the mountain life at Perisher. Have been going for over 40 years. Unfortunately we now have a large international corporation with their own interests at hand, $175 for a day ticket on Saturday has gone too far! Perisher shall begin to lose business at this rate. There are better value options overseas, as well as supporting our local KNP by just xcountry skiing.

column8: Went durimg the October long weekend, and it was great. Snow was a bit patchy in areas, but the skiing was still very enjoyable. Due to COVID, there weren't many crowds, I'll update this review if it's different normally. Only issue is gear hire, which is pretty expensive. It's good if you need something urgently, but I'd recommend picking something up on the way instead, since the convinience of hiring at the slopes has a hefty price tag.

column8:
There is a constant trade-off at Perisher between conditions of the snow and the size of the crowds.
The crowds we're average the week we were there because the snow cover was "average" .... at best. When the snow cover is good the place gets very -  very crowded.
They either need to build a much bigger car park or reduce the cost of the ski tube. I would use the ski tube regularly if it was not extortionately expensive.

column8: Perisher is the best ski resort in Australia. It is the largest ski resort (was once three ski resorts, but then they all combined to create Perisher). There is ample amounts of lifts, T-bars everywhere to keep you going all day. A wide variety of greens, blue and black runs to suit everyone. Allow time to get up the skitube from the bottom, as it takes approximately 30 minutes. Lots of restaurants scattered around the resort as well! Happily return here, as it's my favourite place to ski.

Extremely expensive for a day in the snow. Don't mind paying the national park entry, but $190 for a day pass for adult skiing is ridiculous, add to that the exorbitant prices at the on site shops, poor quality of the facilities, and the fact that in general the staff aren't exactly friendly, I'd rather spend my money overseas and ski NZ for a whole lot less.
A week at perisher for a family of 4 would be $3200 just in lift passes, at least, then add on at least the same again for food and accommodation and you've got one expensive off-snow holiday. Staying on snow you'd double that.
The off snow ski hire places are quite reasonably priced, but on snow, you could buy for the price of a hire. 80 a day for a pair of ski pants at the resort?
The resort itself offers sort of reasonable skiing, but really, it's only just better than nothing.
NZ, the US and Canada, even Europe offer far better skiing, for a whole lot less money and much better resorts and runs. Sure there's a cost to get there, but if you are after a couple of weeks of great skiing,  don't go here.

column8: We made a cancellation request on 25 June for bundle passes on 3&4 July due to covid restrictions. Under either old or new cancelation policies, we are eligible for the refunds. It’s been one month since the request, we emailed 4 times to follow up as I don’t hear any response nor updates but the auto email reply. Called them but never answered. It’s not just poor customer service, but violates our customer rights. Leaving a feedback now also considering other escalation channels.

column11:
Great place for all ages. The kids had a ball. The ski instructors where fantastic although obviously wanted to entice them back for more lessons.
We has a great time and will be back, logs of mountain to explore and runs for all types. Simggins holes is fantastic for the kids with short lift lines and plenty of tracks.

column8: I buggered my knee day 1 of 5. Perisher Ski Resort were super friendly and helpful in response. They guided me to the medical centre. column8:
Probably the biggest ski resort with some beautiful slopes between snow gums, if you want to ski in Australia in the snowy mountains!
That's why I give it any stars at all.
The reason why the the managing company should rethink their business model:
Their prices are a complete rip off: $199/1day ski pass and only half of the lifts open is not ok.
But worse than that: in this price the public transport with the ski tube or shuttle bus is not included, so most people prefer to drive their own cars up which is absolutely counterproductive for our environment.
Not any discounts at their ticket terminals even in the peak Covid season, no half day passes or 4 out of 5-passes etc.
Pricing policy is a complete failure and no, they don't have to make their money in 3 months...other resorts worlwide are in a similar situation and they manage to offer deals in other seasons for hikers, bikers and many more potential customers.
Guess, they have to re-think their business model, anyway they won't have my money again.
Skiing in NZ or in a 5-star Switzerland skiresort is cheaper. What a pitty!

column8:
I contacted customer services via the online form on the 13th June 2021.  I've  sent 2 follow up emails and messaged the team on facebook. I've  have had no reply.

The reason for contacting customer services was regarding the 9.45 Ski tube from Bullocks Flat to Perisher on Saturday 12th June.

The tube ride was a terrifying experience that was handled poorly by Perisher Ski Resort.  There was no communication from the conductor as to what was going on.  No PA system for them to communicate with us.  Children were crying and terrified.  People were confused and panicked about what was going on and what they should be doing. Smoke was filling the train and we were told the train was on fire.  It brings to the fore the questionable safety measures and emergency evacuation plans in place for the train service.

After an emergency exit we had to walk the remaining way on the train tracks with ski gear and small, crying children.

In addition, earlier that day I had to line up for 40 minutes at Bullocks Flat despite having booked everything online the prior day because the required email and QR code was not sent.

The "mountain money" offered to us late in the day is grossly inadequate, is not useful to us and in no way compensates for the experience of that morning.  It took another hour to calm down my family.  We lost an expensive half day of skiing due to the experience of the Perisher Skitube

Please respond to my emails.

column8: We left Sydney 9am today just to ensure we can make it to the night ski session. Arrived Jindabyne at 4:30pm and quickly had dinner. But when arrived V8 nothing was running. Lifts have closed and snow was not groomed. I instantly realised the night ski session must’ve been ended. We were extremely disappointed. The night ski was still running last Saturday and there is no notification or information on the website or dashboard warning us  the night ski has ended. If we knew it, we could’ve left sydney a lot later and had a relax trip down here. Our plan would’ve changed completely. The night ski has been opening every saturday for the entire season. It is 29th September today, I don’t understand that if you have your day session open why couldn’t keep the night session or at least highlight to your customer the dates when night sessions are available. There is no information easily spotted on the dashboard or website saying the night session has ended. Terrible experience :(

column8:
The rings themselves are quite good, but everything isn't organised very well. It's a mission to send your kid off to a lesson...
I won't come back until they change their policy about ski lift passes. You have to choose exact consecutive days of purchasing a multi-day pass and no matter what the weather is it's when you have to ski! It's going to be raining next three days and we'll have to stick it up and ski in the rain or just loose our passes.😠
Not good enough! Resorts in New Zealand give you and two weeks your lift tickets, no questions asked. I'll go there instead.

column11:
Perisher is an amazing experience! And definitely worth the drive! Plenty of activities for everyone!
In peak times though trying to get a park cab be difficult, but that's just like any other place!

column8:
The shear fact that it has 4 very different resort areas that are all Li ked by lifts (or ski tube) makes this the best Australian resort for choice of runs and terrain. It always seems to have more snow coverage than it's competitors. Plenty of 'on mountain' areas to eat to escape the larger village food court areas. Good discounts also if you get a season pass.

Be sure to get your national Park pass as rangers check car number plates every day.

Also be aware the car park fills very quickly on weekends. Ski tube from bullocks flat is always a sure thing to beat the car park issue and also saves fitting chains on snowy days.

column8: Always a great experience. Staff do their best. But I completely overwhelmed at peak times. Lessons are at ground level though they make you buy lift tickets. Lift tickets always a rip off. Take caution with everything you do. Especially the T bar lift which people tend to fly off with young children and get stuck halfway up the mountain. It's all part of the thrilling experience but take caution. I think that in future the safety will be improved.

column11: Top place not to busy

column8: I went here in winter as a novice. The weather was cold and rainy. The lesson I'd paid for was too hard for me, I'm a reasonably fit 68 year old. We had very little practice at stopping, it was very slippery, we had to walk up slope sideways over and over which was very tiring. I gave up. I still had a nice time taking photos, riding the ski tube,  having expensive coffee. The scenery is beautiful. They won't let you ride the ski lift up and down,  so I couldn't even do that.

column8: Perisher ski fields are fantastic and we have had so many enjoyable times here however, ordering tickets online is very hard and if you ever get sick and need a refund or credit it is IMPOSSIBLE to get in contact with them. You usually wait at least 20 days for each email reply and the reply is usually unfriendly and not helpful. Don't try calling them, it is impossible to get through. It is such a shame that such a nice place has such a poor customer service attitude.

column8: Premium price of $200 a day at the start of the season and there's brown patches all over the piste, half the lifts aren't open. They claimed the whole mountain was open early but they don't even have all the lifts running. Not even some magic carpets, tbars or lifts operating at the bottom. They seem to open more on the wknd but that's just so packed they only allow a certain amount of people in and aren't even allowing people in that have paid for national park ticket, accom and ski passes. Really badly managed!

column8: Perisher Ski Resort is one of the finest Skiing facilities in Australia. There are ample snow gear hiring options within and around it. There is hot food served within Perisher Ski Resort for a nominal price. Toilet facilities are also available which are frequently maintained and are relatively clean. We were traveling with three kids which included a one year old however the trip went smoothly. Don't forget to arrive early to get a parking spot bearby the resort otherwise, you have to catch a free bus to get there.

column8:
Why can’t the ski school price include lift ticket? I was pulled out of the line twice to organise my sons lift ticket halfway through his lesson. Service desk useless both times, couldn’t fix the problem. Cost me 30minutes each time I had to go and line up to fix the problem with his lesson.  Time is money on the mountain.
Never paid for lift ticket for the first 3 days of lessons, then get caught out on day 4. This doesn’t even take into account the wasted 30minutes at the start of ski school because they have no idea how to organise a bunch of kids eager for ski school. Go check out how other resorts do it Perisher and implement some positive changes. The most disorganised mountain resort I’ve been to. Happy to take the most money for anything and everything but can’t return with decent service.

column8: Perisher was stunning. I have spent only a few holidays in alpine areas and had never ski'd before. I was unable to get a lesson because they were booked out, but I hired ski's and had a go at the bottom. Ended up getting an afternoon lift pass for $185 and spent the second half of the day riding the lifts and skiing the slopes. It's an experience I'll never forget. I hope to get back to Perisher one day!

column8:
What more is there to say about Australia's biggest ski resort? It has something for everyone. The staff are super friendly and it's always refreshing to have a laugh with the lifties on a cold snowy day. The terrain varies so greatly that there are trails for all levels. One of the special things about Perisher is that you can access most parts of the mountain with an access trail. A big favourite is the traverse from Mt Perisher right over to Guthega.

column8: Today the family had a group lesson at Perisher.  We had mixed abilities on the snow as well as a large gap in ages.  I was a tad concerned how it would go.  Do yourself a favour if you get lessons and seek out Dory.  Young energetic bloke, entertaining as well as a great teacher. Without sounding condescending, a very impressive young man.

column8:
Very famous Snow skiing place of Australia. We hire our equipment from Coom on our way to come here because it is much cheaper. High season better not waste your time to search place to stay here as it is super expensive. We choosed a day trip and still have plenty of time to play. There is also place for young families to play Tobago and it is fun!
Parking is a bit issue so better come here early otherwise you won't find a place to park. I think it is about 30/car for entrance fee at the gate of national park.
We brought a portable gas cooker so we can heat our food and made a simple cup of hot coffee.it was delicious!

column8: The ski school booking and management system is very rigid an inflexible. There is no system for easily confirming what classes have been booked and when your upcoming classes are scheduled. It is difficult to make any adjustments or changes. It also not possible to make a future booking with a specific instructor. The only option is to make a request online, however there is no confirmation or guarantee of who you will get, and no refund if your preferred instructor is not available. Improvements could be made in this area. Other than that we enjoy the resort.
column11: The ski school booking and management system is very rigid an inflexible. There is no system for easily confirming what classes have been booked and when your upcoming classes are scheduled. It is difficult to make any adjustments or changes. It also not possible to make a future booking with a specific instructor. The only option is to make a request online, however there is no confirmation or guarantee of who you will get, and no refund if your preferred instructor is not available. Improvements could be made in this area. Other than that we enjoy the resort.

column8:
Wide open spaces, multiple zones to do your desired sport in the snow. But be mindful, food for some reason is 4x more expensive than anything down below, come early or lose parking and you'd have to ride the train up the mountain which cost the same amount of petrol you used from sydney to perisher. What is great is that everything amazing is made by nature, snow, scenery, location... The rest is average to mediocre, like food, toilets, transportation, parking, accommodation, etc etc... All for profit. Still a 4/5 due to the experience.

P.s to whoever is stopping traffic at the intersection of the base of the train station, if they can move further up the road and block traffic that are going straight rather than block even traffic going to the station as it took us and the rest of going to the station 30+mins just to stop for no reason as we were going a different way.

column8: Had such an amazing experience at Perisher, It was my first time ever seeing snow and snowboarding. The staff there were super kind and helpful and the ski hills were well maintained. My main problems were that everything was quite pricey along with the ski hill being extremely busy. Unless you were willing to pay for a lesson the steep slopes were kinda difficult to learn on, Sort of a being thrown into the deep end kind of situation. As for the small area provided for learning it was just far too small for the sheer amount of people in there, any attempt to ski down it would almost certainly end in you taking out a family or two. All and all tho it was such a mystical experience to be able to see snow and learn how to snowboard on it.

column8: Wonderful Resort. Contains runs available for multiple types of riders. Blue cow is Great if you want a slightly quieter slope, which generally has better “snow quality” and more “powder”. The learning slope there is great, and Lessons happen there too, which I recommend more then Front Valley. Speaking about that, Front Valley is Perisher’s main advertised ski learning area, which is not a great area to start off at. The slope is always busy, and too steep to learn on. Great places here to ski with your family (Smiggins Holes, Happy Valley). Just if you’re planning on driving up to Perisher anytime after 8am on the weekend, forget it. Just take the skitube, much easier but it can be busy.

column8: Perisher was alright. It was definitely a great ski resort, with a large variety of ski runs, and many open ski lifts. It had many restaurants and places to eat, however it was extremely crowded. Queues for lifts were much longer than queues I was used to, and the restaurants were extremely crowded. However, Blue Cow and Guthega weren't as crowded as Perisher Valley, so I definitely recommend checking it out there.

column8:
Mixed feelings about Perisher. It has some great slopes and the sheer size of the ski fields is enormous. The staff are super friendly and it seems like a big family of like minded people.

The facilities feel like they are struggling to keep pace with the millions of dollars spent up on the mountain every year. The inflexible way access to the mountain and the chair lifts operates make it hard to justify forking out a small fortune when it feels like a gamble on the weather. Sometimes you win and get consecutive days of great weather but sometimes you don't and just bleed money for nothing in return.

It would be convenient to blame Covid but in reality these things were problems before Covid and nothing has really changed.

A few things that should be on the radar:
- Old and tired locker space needs improving and modernising. Make better use of the space and update the low security padlock/keys to something more 21st Century.
- Some flexibility in lift access passes  such as 3 or 4 days in a week, rather than  enforced consecutive days. Allows you to have a rest day if you like, or take a day off when the weather is poor.
- Same as the previous point with the NSW National Parks access.
- Car parking at Perisher could be vastly improved. The car park is woefully inadequate on busy days. Expanded facilities at Smiggins wouldn't hurt either.

Not expecting miracles. Snow sports will continue to be an expensive option in Australia. I am fortunate to be able to enjoy it.

Came for a feed with friends.  Food wasn't bad but not many food options either.  It was pretty pricy,  and most items averaged at $25+ (not including drinks) but apparently a standard price for perisher.

I ordered the beef lasagna with chips.  You get to choose chips or mash and add vegetables too.
The chips were a good serving size and really nice and crispy.  You could fill up on chicken salt and condiments to your liking on the self serve desk.

The beef lasagna was not bad.  It was a bit mushy in the centre,  however it was a good size and they had a good chunk of cheese on top of the lasagna; just the way I like it.

I ate around 1:30pm and the line was still pretty long,  however not a long wait as they do serve you pretty quickly.  Staff were nice and friendly too.

column8:
Huge ski resort with many and various runs. There is a place for most skiers here and many social media advice pages so I dont need to add to it here except for the following.
A) this place is popular and busy, don't come here to relax.
B) prices are not outrageous but a day of takeaway food costs a lot.
C) skiing early is often icy. The best snow is later in the day.
D) it is very easy to loose friends and family here, bring phones.

column8:
Everything that's wrong with the Australian tourism industry in one place. The place itself is beautiful but ruined by greedy, low service operators.There's no attempt to even pretend anymore that they're not seeking rent by price gouging for access to a priceless national resource.

For example:
- Extremely high prices by global standards.
- All infrastructure and equipment is old and of the cheapest possible quality.
- Simple things like ski racks on the Ski Tube or shelter near the car park are missing.
- Basic services like looking after your shoes after hiring skis and boots not available. "We don't do that". I had to carry my shoes in my backpack or walk a long way back to my car.
- Won't store ski hire overnight. "You have to take them with you mate."
- Don't build capacity to match customer numbers. It's normal to find nowhere to sit at lunchtime.
- Force you to walk all over the place in ski boots. Ski Tube is a couple of hundred metres from the lifts and up and down stairs. Better to save money on a bit of extra track and make your customers walk than take them where they're actually trying to go.
- Basic things like signs are missing. Had to walk around asking people in shops to find the kids ski school.
- Accommodation prices that would get you a 5 star resort elsewhere will get you the equivalent of a dirty hostel here.

Australia needs to wake up that it's not 1980 anymore and visitors expect reasonable prices and good service.

column8: Absolutely wonderful experience as a beginner at Perisher! We booked a beginners class and it was 10/10 worth it. We had 2 wonderful instructors, Andy Aitken and Daisy to the 6 of us and they were absolutely so professional and friendly with their teaching approach. They are clearly experts in their field as I was able to spend the remainder of the days at the snow zipping around thanks to them! All the other staff we encountered on the mountain were also so friendly too. 10/10 will visit again and highly recommend getting lessons!

column8:
Pro's:
-Retains snow well Australian resort
-value season pass
-huge variety of blue runs

Cons:
-Biggest ques I have ever seen (I have been all around the world to many resorts) up to 3 hours waiting on road and at lift in a day
-very flat. (Some runs go uphill for significant length)
-lots of traversing.
-poorly marked trails

column8:
The cost of the ski tube should be included in the **already inflated** lift ticket price. I can't believe Vail expects Aussie punters to pay an extra $87 per person per day for a 10 min journey on an ancient and overcrowded train.. some common sense should prevail..

Perisher + ski tube:
$222 lift ticket
$87 ski tube
$309 total.

Perisher + drive:
$222 lift ticket
$29 national park pass per car

vs

Thredbo + drive
$189 lift ticket
$29 national park pass per car
$218

column8:
Great place, given Australian options, but:
- It feels like the majority of staff are very unhappy - apparently let down by management.
- Personally experienced some lifts and T-bars were stopping intermittently due to (quote) 'poor maintenance'. And lastly;
- They are incredibly misleading with their forecasts (chairs expected open, and on-mountain parking as just two examples). I feel for the families forking out thousands to spend 2+hours crawling up the mountain in a queue of cars 14+km long, only to find the parking is full, and their options are fork out another large amount for SkiTube, or just not go.

Again many positives but Perisher desperately needs to pick up their act to improve these items and more. But hey, they've got a captured market so I'm not holding my breath unfortunately.

column8:
Yes, it was fun, but not really worth the cost any more.
Always beautiful, but getting increasingly hard to look past paying over $200 a day to ski Australian snow and having to park about a kilometre and a half away and walk up due to lack of parking by 7 in the morning. The park closures almost every day are completely justified (as there is no room for anyone) but ridiculous for paying customers as it seems like there is no viable solution on the horizon despite releasing the 40 year management plan and by 7am you physically cannot drive beyond Jindabyne due to grid lock. Will be interesting to see what happens before the biggest resort in Australia gets driven into the ground.

column8: Fantastic snow. Quick lifts. Great instruction. Friendly staff. Only negative was that it was a bit expensive but to me it was worth it. I'm totally recharged!!

column8:
This place is a money hungry joke, all the staff were so incredibly rude, in guest services and on the lifts.
We had a family emergency and we are not able to ride the following day and as we pre purchased our tickets, we were declined our refund by the manager, we did email the day before (24 hours) before the slopes opened the next day.
In the terms in conditions it does not state that cancellations must be made at 12am today for our tickets for tomorrow. We have snow boarded around the world and have never experienced this kind of poor service and to think this is in our own country is very upsetting, will not be returning. If you are thinking of coming this way for the snow, definitely visit Thredbo over this ridiculously overpriced and money hungry place.

column8: Do not honour season pass refunds. A consistent issue, well known by the ACCC and fair trading. column8:
Perisher has gone down hill with customer service and the knowledge of their staff. They have changed all the seating at the perisher centre making it hard for kids to sit and eat their food.

And now thanks to Gerry Harvey and Covid everything on Hill is so expensive with a bottle of water costing $5.35 even with the epic discount.

It is what it is, if you want to ski and board in Australia then this is what you have to put up with now. Don't expect a cheap holiday just enjoy what we have, their pass is reasonably priced so there is that going for it so weigh it all up.

column8: First time to go to this place. We parked at the roadside, very far from the site coz the parking spaces were already full. But there are buses that will take passengers to the site for FREE. These buses will also take passengers back to the roadside parking for FREE. So nothing to worry if u arrive late to enjoy the day at the site.

column8: Quite a different season 2022. I think overall they managed reasonably well with a lot of the challenges. One grumble is that the food at all of the resort owned restaurants is significantly more expensive than it used to be whilst the quality has dropped extremely. When dining on mountain you accept that it's going to cost more most of the food on offer is absolute garbage.

column8:
It was me and my wife’s first time at perisher. We started with hiring the equipment that we needed. The two girls that were their were very helpful and helped us choose the right gear and the right sizes all with a smile on their face. We then went on to skiing and we struggled bad lol and unfortunately there were no lessons left and it was our first time skiing. The girls after seeing our struggle came out of their way and sacrificed their lunch break to teach some key skills and what a difference that made. They even took us up the skii lift and down the mountain while helping us the whole way. We actually started to enjoy skiing.

Talija and Zahli thank you very very much. Words cannot describe how thankful we are. Your smiles and sacrifice meant so much to us and it made our experience unforgettable.

column8: I hadn’t been to the snow in 6 years and cannot believe the price of a lift ticket. Especially considering the crowds there. Some lift queues took 40 minutes. Everything else, I would have given 5 stars but the lift ticket and overcrowding needs to be immediately addressed. It was so hard to  spend almost $200 a day on the ticket alone. I love skiing but I don’t think it’s worth it for that price. I’ll find somewhere more reasonable.

column8: It would’ve been five stars if it hadn’t been for the nasty comments from Josh about our “mentally slow” fellow learners. on the first day, we had Joe and he was amazing and very encouraging and compassionate. He walked us through the process and understood that snowboarding is challenging. to our surprise, on the second day we had Josh and and he was rude and made snarky comments about our performance. We had never been snowboarding before and were new to the sport and we deserved more respect then what we were given.

column8:
snow was surprisingly great for September and was very well kept. All of the chair and T bar were up and running and the queues were short. Some of the runs were a bit icy but not too bad and could be skied right over. I recommend you leave as early as possible to get a parking spot because it gets insanely packed very quickly. I would recommend getting there at around 7:30 which gives you the best chance at getting a good parking. Also giving you the longest amount of time to be able to ski.

The snow was so incredible considering it’s almost the end of the season.. So grateful for the big 60cm dump last weekend..
Was gorgeously sunny first couple days & got cold & misty today that added to the experience..
was very well kept…
All of the chair and T bar were up and running and the queues were short. Some of the runs were a bit icy but not too bad and could be skied right over..
Some of the tracks that are super icy are closed but it won’t deter you from having fun & creating memories..
I recommend you leave as early as possible to get a parking spot as it fills pretty quickly & they’ve now extended the season due to the incredible conditions yay
because it gets insanely packed very quickly…
I’m sure you’ll have a blast !
Go get out & explore !

column11:
The snow was so incredible considering it’s almost the end of the season.. So grateful for the big 60cm dump last weekend..
Was gorgeously sunny first couple days & got cold & misty today that added to the experience..
was very well kept…
All of the chair and T bar were up and running and the queues were short. Some of the runs were a bit icy but not too bad and could be skied right over..
Some of the tracks that are super icy are closed but it won’t deter you from having fun & creating memories..
I recommend you leave as early as possible to get a parking spot as it fills pretty quickly & they’ve now extended the season due to the incredible conditions yay
because it gets insanely packed very quickly…
I’m sure you’ll have a blast !
Go get out & explore !
Fun

Had a wonderful one day ski trip here, the snow was amazing and the lift lines were relatively short, heaps of lifts open and a good variety of slopes. It was super easy and quick to get our lift passes. The biggest downside was the massive price for one day lift passes and it was difficult to get up the mountain in a 2 wheel drive if you don't want to pay for the ski tube. Overall a good experience.

column8:
Brilliant place to ski with lots of places to stop and have a drink.or a bite to eat. We always ski at the end of the season and it never disappoints. Blue skies and sunshine with lots of different runs to use. Who could ask for more?
On weekends and on school holidays the carpark fills up quickly so don’t turn up later than 9 am or you’ll be parking on the street and walking.
To make life easier for yourself HIRE A LOCKER for both your boots and skis if you are on the slopes for several days.
It makes a huge difference both before and after you ski.
Apart from that watch out for fellow skiers and have fun!

column11:
Brilliant place to ski with lots of places to stop and have a drink.or a bite to eat. We always ski at the end of the season and it never disappoints. Blue skies and sunshine with lots of different runs to use. Who could ask for more?
On weekends and on school holidays the carpark fills up quickly so don’t turn up later than 9 am or you’ll be parking on the street and walking.
To make life easier for yourself HIRE A LOCKER for both your boots and skis if you are on the slopes for several days.
It makes a huge difference both before and after you ski.
Apart from that watch out for fellow skiers and have fun!

column8:
Had to cancel Epic Pass for 2023 due to injury. Contacted them via phone the computer said only contact via email. Then I sent multiple emails with no reply. Very bad service. Not only me having this problem after reading the reviews. One said: Do not honour season pass refunds. A consistent issue, well known by the ACCC and fair trading. They’ll take your money in a heart beat, but you’ll never hear from them when lodging a refund request (supported by the correct paperwork as dictated by their own T&Cs). No way to contact them aside from email; and as mentioned, good luck getting a response. Appalling CS.'

I Totally agree

It is a great place for a family holiday but of course it is expensive especially for a family. A bit crowded on the weekends and holidays so more toilets with fresh air and carparks would help. The Train also gets over crowded and is expensive. But memories forever.
Try to be early and have a big breakfast to keep you going. Staff, lifts , scenery are fantastic. Some healthier food options would be appreciated.
Probably be back again this year so I guess I rate it. 🏂✌️

Took the kids there last winter and had a great day out with the toboggans in the designated area without having to pay the chair lift fees. They also had a tube ride, which cost extra, but it was fun. Make sure you get back to the car by the time the sun sets, as it gets icy cold really quickly.

column8:
Lift ticket prices keep going up, but fail to see any improvement of either the carpark, the park facilities, the volume of people, or customer service of Perisher staff.

I’ll save my money and head overseas.

column8:
The perisher park is great. The staff situation for the obsene amount of money we paid and the complete lack of parking was killing me. 1 hour long lines on snow days. And un maintained t-bar runs meant that i ended up my a split lip and a missing goggle lense from a mass set of whoops in the middle of the tbar, my daughter hurt her leg, my friend fractured a rib because the under the t-bar was not maintained for 4 days.
And i pay for that very thing. If it happens next this year you can expect to get the bills.

column8:
Go here almost every year and it is always great! Has a great variety of runs of varying length and difficulty so there is an option for everyone. Some of my personal favourite runs include; kamikaze (a harder run for older and more experienced skiers) and rollercoaster in Blue Cow, Wood Run (great for kids and new skiers) and Blanchy's in Smiggins Holes, Powder Ridge (probably the easiest black thats ever open) and Goat's Gully in Front Valley Towers run and GS Bowl (should be a black) in Mount Perisher, and Easy Rider (very long but easy) and Mother in Law in Guthega.

Perisher also has great cafes and other restaurants/food places throughout for a great break from skiing with excellent food and drinks, my personal favourite and recommendation is the Pretty Valley Kiosk due to its incredible hot chocolates. If you are in Front Valley during lunch I would also recommend taking a trip to the Perisher Centre as it has a series of restaurants, cafes and shops to buy ski gear if yours breaks.

Even though Perisher Resort is huge, if you are even just an intermediate skier you can pretty easily make it the whole way around the resort and back if you know the way or just follow the signs as they are very helpful.

Not to may complaints just some of the lifts are old and please replace the Pretty Valley Double Chair, it is only about 1km yet it feels like it takes 15min, please speed it up, please.

column8:
Terrible lift management, no single queues and not filling up all chairs despite hordes of people waiting. Very disrespectful towards queueing people having purchased expensive lift passes and want to get value for money and get as much time on the slopes as possible. They should look at how it’s managed in places like Norway instead and adopt industry best practices in lift management..

column8:
Getting worse every year.

On 22nd of june, Only 10% of the mountain open for boarding yet $189 for a day lift pass. Takes 30 seconds to finish the trail but 5 mins for lift queue. I understand that not enough snow at the this time but why charge such prices. Nowhere in the world is this expensive at this quality.

Toboggoning area is marked as "closed" so kids suppose to have what fun??  In thredbo, no tobogganing either? How can these guys call it "family fun?"

column8: Loved this mountain till I spoke 2 minutes with head of pathways Katie Kreczman. She has absolutely no customer service skills and was the most rude individual I have ever encountered in 45 years of skiing and 25 years skiing with vail resorts around the world. Husband worked for them for years and he couldn’t believe the way Katie spoke and reacted to a basic query of why kids weren’t training on the race flags set up and why kids who are 6 not the correct  the age of the program less than 100 cm tall and can’t ski a black run or can’t buckle their boots in the program taking up all the coaches time. If you can’t  handle a question and falsely advertise a program you shouldn’t be working for vail resorts. Hotham and Thredbo are now my favorites in Australia. Don’t bother here it’s too crowded and the lifts are all on wind hold every five seconds with hour long lines and terrible customer service.

column8: Dated facilities and crowded! Its time to upgrade and update your facilities. You are charging mega bucks but your services and basic facilities are nowhere near what we are paying. No public free wifi - this is the basic service you should provide! Proper seating with charging facilities. Not everyone who visits Perisher actually going skiing! Parents have nowhere to go when others are skiing away! Food prices are exorbitant! $9 for a bottle of drink? $23.50 for a kebab? Seriously??? Locker facilities have been updated recently and so has the prices! A small locker will set you back $22 per night? Its now cheaper to go skiing overseas like Queenstown and Japan. You will never be able to boost the local tourism with these. Reflection required!

column8:
Perisher charges a premium for its name and yet is unable to manage their lifts operation effectively to service the skiers. I was there from Thursday last week till Saturday and most lifts were closed. The funny thing was that the triple lift in sniffing a was open and not the tBar, wind on Saturday was strong but wasn’t too bad and surely the tBar could be operated. I heard that they were understaffed which makes sense. Whilst they knew is going to be windy they still advertise that they are going to open the lifts but in reality only 2 lifts were open in perisher.
I take my money somewhere else to ski who doesn’t

column8:
We went late June for one day at Perisher, and were very fortunate enough to have vivid fresh snow. We parked at Bullocks Flat, took the Skitube and got off at Perisher Valley, hurried over to Perisher Centre to get rental snow jacket and pants, and the skiing boots, helmet and skis. Goggles and neck scarfs are byo or buy in venue and are recommended on very snowy days. Bags and shoes placed in small-ish rental lockers that were roughly the size of a microwave each. We took the 9am beginners lesson and the instructors are very friendly. All this was easily booked and paid online via the perisher website where you’ll get a QR code to scan at the ticket machines there and print out a Mountain access card for each person. Like some others have said, Perisher Valley isn’t the most beginner friendly, even their Front Valley slope is steep in some areas and need decent steering skills to minimise falling over. Thredbo has a better kid and beginner friendly area close to ground. The queues to the chairlifts are iconically long during the winter peak + school holidays period but they do take you quite high up the mountain so it’s worth the thrill gliding down.

column11: We went late June for one day at Perisher, and were very fortunate enough to have vivid fresh snow. We parked at Bullocks Flat, took the Skitube and got off at Perisher Valley, hurried over to Perisher Centre to get rental snow jacket and pants, and the skiing boots, helmet and skis. Goggles and neck scarfs are byo or buy in venue and are recommended on very snowy days. Bags and shoes placed in small-ish rental lockers that were roughly the size of a microwave each. We took the 9am beginners lesson and the instructors are very friendly. All this was easily booked and paid online via the perisher website where you’ll get a QR code to scan at the ticket machines there and print out a Mountain access card for each person. Like some others have said, Perisher Valley isn’t the most beginner friendly, even their Front Valley slope is steep in some areas and need decent steering skills to minimise falling over. Thredbo has a better kid and beginner friendly area close to ground. The queues to the chairlifts are iconically long during the winter peak + school holidays period but they do take you quite high up the mountain so it’s worth the thrill gliding down.

The private lesson instructor Laura ended private class earlier than the time should be. The private lesson should be end at 4 but Laura ended at 3.43 pm one the first day and 3.40 pm on the second day. Even after the parent communicated with her to end class at 4 pm or at least between 3.45pm - 4 pm she insisted to end the class at 3.40pm. One day of the whole day private lesson cost 1277 AUD and the duration of the class should be from 9am-4pm. Make complainant to the instructor’s supervisor, a female supervisor always said she would contact the parent but never did. A male supervisor said he would call back but till we leave the resort he hasn’t talked to us about how to solve it.

Perisher has some good ski runs, but there are too many T-bar ski lifts with too many snowboarders who keep falling off. It impacts the enjoyment of all skiers, this is compounded by very mixed ski quality. In Australia this counts as a good ski resort, but in many cases you can fly to another country and get better skiing for less money.

column8: Absolutely rubbish. Blue cow lifts are still on hold today, tons of ppl have to queuing at V8. Those who need an easy green to practice have no other option and have to use this only opened lift. It is a slow zone but  experts still flying though this only opened beginners zone. Perisher Express quad is still closed. Pleasant Valley still closed. The easy starter in Blue Cow is also still close. Go to Thredbo next time, they open more lifts than perisher.

Took 3 hours to get up to the carpark because of heavy traffic.
Lift lines were way to long and slow. 45min waiting time is ridiculous considering the $250 ticket price.
Staff were useless and ornamental. Better to go to a professional resort overseas.

column8: Place is nice, life passes are expensive tough. close to $200 per day per person, has the most lifts in Australia and you can explore 4 mountains. For beginners, front valley is not a great place, it's actually steeper than some other runs like pretty valley and happy valley. views from top is fantastic during bluebird day. base become crowded from 12:30 as the lessons finish at 1 and hard to find the seat during peak hours. Great for families.

column8: I find that all Perisher 'Lifties' are lovely and friendly but we met a wonderfully helpful Lift Ticket checker at the Perisher Quad Express by the name of Joël who was beyond kind and helpful to my daughter and I when she misplaced her phone. Due to Joël's helpful assurance and kindness, we were able to successfully find my daughter's phone and ensure that the rest of our vacation at Perisher was not ruined. Thank you so much again Joël and we hope to see you again next year!!

Drove to Canberra the day before. Took a shuttle at 5am the next day to Bullocks Flat for SkiTube. Got our gear in Bullocks Flat and have to carry them around all day. Should have picked them up at Perisher Valley. Spent 5 hours on the beginner slope. Left at 3pm. Back to Canberra at 7pm.

The day we were there, there was a snow harzard @ -2.2°C. We had to get ourselves skimasks and goggles on top of our 5 layers of clothes and 3 layers of pants.

Should have booked their 2 hrs learning lessons. You'll need lift tickets unless you plan to sit it out. Kids are mandatory to wear a helmet.

Plenty choices for lunch, but it was difficult to get a seat. The place was crowded with people.

Bullocks Flat was snowing on our way back. So glad we didn't drive ourselves.

column8:
Went for vacation to Perisher, didn’t stay there. Reasonable food options until 3PM, transport-
ski tube frequency is okay every 30 minutes but always crowded.
Car drive is great but not on snowy days, check the weather before you start. You need to pay $30 for round trip
Free bus shuttle frequency from Perisher to Smiggins hole is very good
Atmosphere- awesome
Cost - very expensive accommodation but food cost is fine
Ski rentals- Need advance booking
